The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Sponsorship deal finalised
New Delhi: Samsung has bagged the coveted title sponsorship rights for the cricket series between India and Pakistan beginning next month. Although the deal amount was not revealed officially, sources said that it was around Rs 20 crore. Two-wheeler major Hero Honda won the rights as co-sponsors while world sports group Nimbus was granted rights for ground sponsorship. The Indian team is scheduled to tour Pakistan for three Tests and five one-dayers in March-April. Meanwhile, adds a report from Islamabad, the BCCI delegation on Tuesday met top Pakistan interior ministry officials and Indian high commissioner before inspecting the arrangements at the Rawalpindi Stadium, one of the proposed venues for the upcoming series. The BCCI delegation, which includes IGP Yashovardhan Azad, held talks on the security arrangements with secretary, Pakistan interior ministry, Tasnim Noorani who apprised them of the elaborate measures that would be in place. After talks with Noorani, the delegation met Indian high commissioner Shivshankar Menon in Islamabad. Menon later said the officials wanted to visit all the proposed six venues and then review the arrangements. So far the tour to Pakistan is on. During their eight-day stay in Pakistan, the delegation will visit Peshawar, Multan, Karachi, Faisalabad besides Lahore to inspect the stadiums there as well as to hear the presentations by the local police.  (PTI)  Copyright 
